{"kind":"cas-record-v1","metadata":{"entries":[{"origin_package":"github.com/codalotl/codalotl/internal/cli","target_package":"github.com/codalotl/codalotl/internal/gocode","identifier":"*Module.ClonePackage","question":"Does ClonePackage copy only the package's selected Go files into the cloned module package directory, or can it recursively copy subdirectories as well? I need to know whether cloning both parent and nested packages into one clone can interfere.","answer":"`Module.ClonePackage` copies only the package’s selected Go files into that package directory in the cloned module. It does not recursively copy subdirectories.\n\nEvidence from implementation in `internal/gocode/module.go`:\n\n- Destination is exactly `filepath.Join(m.AbsolutePath, pkg.RelativeDir)`.\n- It calls `os.MkdirAll(destDir, 0755)`.\n- It iterates only:\n  - `pkg.Files`\n  - `pkg.TestPackage.Files`, if present\n- For each file it writes `filepath.Join(destDir, name)` using the file’s in-memory `Contents`.\n- There is no directory walk, no recursive copy, and no copying of non-Go files.\n\nSo cloning both a parent and nested package into the same cloned module should not interfere by recursive copying. For example:\n\n- Cloning parent package `\"\"` writes only its own files into clone root.\n- Cloning nested package `\"foo/bar\"` writes only its own files into `clone/foo/bar`.\n- Cloning the parent later does not remove or overwrite `clone/foo/bar`; `ClonePackage` does not delete existing contents.\n\nThe main interference risk would be cloning two packages with the same `RelativeDir`, or if their selected file names collide in the same destination directory. Parent/nested packages with distinct relative dirs should be safe from this specific concern."}]},"additional_info":{"unix_timestamp":1780609906,"paths":["internal/gocode/SPEC.md","internal/gocode/buildconfig.go","internal/gocode/buildconfig_test.go","internal/gocode/cwd.go","internal/gocode/discover_modules.go","internal/gocode/dis